default&#xa0;
default2.2 
defaultParliamentdefault 
defaulthas been misled by the claim that, under EU rules, FITs have to count against public expenditure defaultlimitsdefault. defaultThis UK interpretation has been held to despite the existence of a European court ruling (in Germany's 
defaultfavour
default) to the contrary. When asked, European Commission officials have consistently said that this is entirely down to UK interpretation rather than European determination.
default&#xa0;default2.3 In Germany, FITs are an independent element within energy sector accounting. They do not count as publicdefault defaultexpendituredefault. The government sets the tariffs and regulates their adjustment. The original UK 
defaultprogramme
default was designed to operate in the same way, until it was put into the Levy Control Framework in 2010.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default2.4 The effect of this has been to limit the ability of FITs to turn the existing UK energy cartel into more open and competitive energy market.
default&#xa0;
default2.5 
defaultThedefault 
defaultUK'sdefault 
defaultnarrowdefault 
defaultapproach to 'green' financial mechanisms defaulthas beendefault reinforced by itsdefault&#xa0;defaultdecision to pass all the costs ofdefault defaultFITs defaultprogrammesdefault to consumers, but none of the benefits.default In Germany there is a duty on the Grid to take 'clean' renewable energy (supported by FITs) before 'dirty'. This has led to a dramatic fall in their peak (wholesale) electricity prices and promoted substantial private investment in Green energy.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default2.6 
