default&#xa0;default6default.default Critical lessons for the UK default&#xa0;
default6.1 The most consistent questions that arise in all the Anglo-German discussions I have been involved in are "Why does there seem to be one set of EU rules for the Germans and another for Britain?", or "Why is something that we are told would be a breach of State Aid rules in the UK, not
default count as
default one in Germany?".
default&#xa0;
default6.2 The most consistent answer is that
default (
defaultwith the exception of
default attempts to get
default new nuclear
default counted as 'Green' energy)
default British Ministers and officials usually 
defaultgo to the European Commission
default looking for a "No".
default&#xa0;
defaultA progressive and imaginative approach to financing the Green economy falls exactly into this category.
default&#xa0;
default     "The trouble with the British is that you can't take 'Yes' for an answer".
default&#xa0;
default6.3 From the insanely complex (and costly) structure of Green Deal, to the reliance on energy companies to deliver (over-priced) ECO refurbishment, to the retreat from national energy efficiency standards and the fixed-budget (and ever
default 
defaultchanging) constraints on renewable energy generation, 
defaultUK policies on Green Finance seem designed to defaultmarginalisedefault its role and to prop up the powers of the UK's existing energy carteldefault.
default&#xa0;
default6.4 The UK government has placed itself, and the GIB, in a secondary role in the energy transformation process. 
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTreasury interests in non-renewable energy usually trump DECC interests in renewables. 
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultProgrammes
default to radically reduce energy consumption get displaced in 
defaultfavour
default of lower regulatory requirements. 
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA race to the bottom has replaced the race to the top.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default6.5 In Denmark, the Netherlands, Scandinavia, France, Italy and Spain, as well as Germany, there are abundant examples of clearer, simpler frameworks that deliver Green Finance, on a transformational scale, against more ambitious national 'renewable energy' targets.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
